    "summary": "After over 30 years with PwC, Gareth will be looking for new opportunities from June 2022, and will consider interesting projects, and employment and board room opportunities, particularly in the US, Japan, Australia, and Asia. \n__________________________________________________________________\n\nGareth is an accountant, auditor and financial advisor with wide ranging experience of the banking industry. His expertise spans IFRS, particularly financial instrument accounting, financial reporting, risk and regulation, the valuation of derivatives and other financial instruments, GAAP conversion, litigation support, and buy/sell side due diligence. He has worked in the UK, Japan, Australia, Indonesia, and the Netherlands.\n\nRecent project experience\n- From 2017 to 2020, technical advisor in connection with the Euro 1 billion derivatives mis-selling compensation programs run by Dutch banks and supervised by the Dutch regulator (the AFM).  \n- Over the past ten years, financial advisor to the Euro 25 billion Dutch Lehman estate. This project involved: valuation of 3,800 structured Notes and a number of swap books; negotiation of valuation principles and settlements; litigation support; and restructuring advice in connection with the partial wind-down of the estate. \n- In 2016, appointed by a number of major banks as their global IFRS 9 technical and implementation advisor.\n- In 2016, led root cause investigation of a major restatement of earnings by a high profile listed company, and advised on the implications of the resulting material control weakness on the company\u2019s 20F US filing, reporting to the Audit Committee and Supervisory Board.\n- In 2012, financial advisor to an insolvent Dutch Housing Corporation (Vestia). Vestia collapsed as a result of margin calls on a portfolio of some Euro 30 billion of derivative trades with a consortium of 15 banks.\n- From 2008 to 2010, lead financial advisor to the Dutch Ministry of Finance in connection with its nationalisation of Fortis Bank and ABN Amro. The advice focused on capital and liquidity risks and needs; development of recapitalisation options; negotiation and resolution of separation issues with RBS and Bank Santander; State Aid negotiations; and the spin-off of businesses to third party purchasers.  \n- Advisor to a significant bank in connection with the ECB\u2019s Asset Quality Review and Stress Test. This 11-month project focused on: adequacy of provisioning for corporate and retail loans, data quality issues; development of new provisioning models; and presentation of stress test outcomes to the regulator. \n\n",
